04206nam a22006855i 9789814818506DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182018si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898148185067 a10.1355/97898148185062doi  a(DE-B1597)522117  a(OCoLC)1049909633  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aJQ1062.A95bS47 2018 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a324.95952231 aRahman, Serina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMalaysia’s General Elections 2018 :bUnderstanding the Rural Vote /cSerina Rahman. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (37 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tINTRODUCTION -- tTHE HISTORY OF VOTING IN JOHOR AND KEDAH -- tMETHODOLOGY -- tETHNOGRAPHY OF THE RURAL VOTER -- tTHE ISSUES THAT MATTER -- tNEW DEVELOPMENTS ON THE GROUND -- tAT THE POLLS — ANYONE’S CALL …0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study was carried out in Johor and Kedah through a combination of focus groups, formal and informal interviews and long-term ethnographic participant observation. Johor was selected for this study because it is the birthplace and long-time bastion of UMNO while Kedah was of interest because of the Mahathir family legacy in the state. The study shows that the rural vote is not homogeneous; views and perceptions that could lead to electoral action differs between regions, ages and genders. Daily survival and rising costs of living are the key common issues that were raised across all regions. The importance of Malay rights and the priority of Islam are also important to the rural voter. Another common problem mentioned is that of the middleman who prevents allocated funds or financial assistance from reaching the average rural resident. Malay cultural norms, traditional obligations of loyalty and patronage politics are major factors that affect the decisions of older rural voters. Younger voters might be open to the idea of a new government, but they need to overcome community and family pressure to break away from generational practices of voting for Barisan Nasional. Some rural voters feel that they gain no benefits from having either side of the political divide in power. While these voters generally do not see the point of voting, a last-minute decision to vote may go the way of the party that provides them with immediate gains.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aElectionszMalaysia. 4aCampaigns & Elections. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z978311071955008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060677540uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981481850640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814818506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814818506.jpg  a978-3-11-060677-5  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-071955-0  DG Plus eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK